<font color="#FF0000">SIGNS, SIGNS EVERYWHERE A SIGN</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jul 31 17:08:33 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Signs, signs everywhere a sign, do this don't do that, can't you read the signs.<br><br>
When I first arrived in Vietnam we were greeting at the transit barracks by a loud speaker. <br><br>
&quot;Welcome to the Republic of Viet Nam.  Please report to the front of the depot and convert all US Currency into MPC (Military Payment Certificates. <br><br>
We were told to stay near the transit barrack and wait for further instructions. All around us, Marines in various stages of transit lounged around the depot. Dozens of Marines were sitting around waiting, eating, or playing cards. A hand painted sign of the wall read,<br><br>
&quot;NO LOITERING&quot; <br><br>
When we were send out to our companies, the truck I was riding in slowed down to make a left turn toward Hill 37 from convoy road which was also known as route 5, but roads in Vietnam did not have a sign. <br>
Our maps had route 4 imprinted on them, but the Marine Corps referred to it as route 14, however since the Army printed the maps we used and they had more maps and supplies then we had we used route 4.  <br><br>
As we slowed to turn, I noticed a large 4' by 6' plywood sign on the right side of the road. White lettering on a dark gray background announced sites of interest in the vicinity. <br><br>
An arrow pointing straight ahead read, <br>
Downtown Dai Loc, Hill 65, Hill 52, and points East.<br><br>
A second arrow pointed to the left, which was the road we were turning on. The lettering said, <br>
Hill 37, Thu Bon River, An Hoa and points south. Hill 55 and points east.<br><br>
Another left turning arrow just below that arrow, read;<br>
Gas, Food, Lodging, and Ammo.<br><br>

